# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: digital-twin
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] CPS involves transdisciplinary approaches, merging theory of cybernetics, mechatronics, design and process science.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] The process control is often referred to as embedded systems.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] In embedded systems, the emphasis tends to be more on the computational elements, and less on an intense link between the computational and physical elements.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] CPS is also similar to the Internet of Things (IoT), sharing the same basic architecture; nevertheless, CPS presents a higher combination and coordination between physical and computational elements.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] Examples of CPS include smart grid, autonomous automobile systems, medical monitoring, industrial control systems, robotics systems, recycling and automatic pilot avionics.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] Precursors of cyber-physical systems can be found in areas as diverse as aerospace, automotive, chemical processes, civil infrastructure, energy, healthcare, manufacturing, transportation, entertainment, and consumer appliances.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] Unlike more traditional embedded systems, a full-fledged CPS is typically designed as a network of interacting elements with physical input and output instead of as standalone devices.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] The notion is closely tied to concepts of robotics and sensor networks with intelligence mechanisms proper of computational intelligence leading the pathway.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] Ongoing advances in science and engineering improve the link between computational and physical elements by means of intelligent mechanisms, increasing the adaptability, autonomy, efficiency, functionality, reliability, safety, and usability of cyber-physical systems.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] Mobile cyber-physical systems, in which the physical system under study has inherent mobility, are a prominent subcategory of cyber-physical systems.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] Examples of mobile physical systems include mobile robotics and electronics transported by humans or animals.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] The rise in popularity of smartphones has increased interest in the area of mobile cyber-physical systems.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] Examples of mobile cyber-physical systems include applications to track and analyze CO2 emissions, detect traffic accidents, insurance telematics and provide situational awareness services to first responders, measure traffic, and monitor cardiac patients.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] Common applications of CPS typically fall under sensor-based communication-enabled autonomous systems.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] For example, many wireless sensor networks monitor some aspect of the environment and relay the processed information to a central node.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] Other types of CPS include smart grid, autonomous automotive systems, medical monitoring, process control systems, distributed robotics, recycling and automatic pilot avionics.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] A real-world example of such a system is the Distributed Robot Garden at MIT in which a team of robots tend a garden of tomato plants.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] This system combines distributed sensing (each plant is equipped with a sensor node monitoring its status), navigation, manipulation and wireless networking.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] A focus on the control system aspects of CPS that pervade critical infrastructure can be found in the efforts of the Idaho National Laboratory and collaborators researching resilient control systems.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] This effort takes a holistic approach to next generation design, and considers the resilience aspects that are not well quantified, such as cyber security, human interaction and complex interdependencies.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] Another example is MIT's ongoing CarTel project where a fleet of taxis work by collecting real-time traffic information in the Boston area.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] Together with historical data, this information is then used for calculating fastest routes for a given time of the day.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] CPS are also used in electric grids to perform advanced control, especially in the smart grids context to enhance the integration of distributed renewable generation.The Special remedial action scheme are needed to limit the current flows in the grid when wind farm generation is too high.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] In industry the cyber-physical systems empowered by Cloud technologies have led to novel approaches that paved the path to Industry 4.0 as the European Commission IMC-AESOP project with partners such as Schneider Electric, SAP, Honeywell, Microsoft etc. demonstrated.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] In the area of digital agriculture (alternately precision agriculture), CPS technologies are used for measurement of soil quality and moisture content and determining the right level of irrigation or fertilizer or pesticide usage.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] A challenge in the development of embedded and cyber-physical systems is the large differences in the design practice between the various engineering disciplines involved, such as software and mechanical engineering.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] Additionally, as of today there is no "language" in terms of design practice that is common to all the involved disciplines in CPS.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] Today, in a marketplace where rapid innovation is assumed to be essential, engineers from all disciplines need to be able to explore system designs collaboratively, allocating responsibilities to software and physical elements, and analyzing trade-offs between them.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] Recent advances show that coupling disciplines by using co-simulation will allow disciplines to cooperate without enforcing new tools or design methods.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] Results from the MODELISAR project show that this approach is viable by proposing a new standard for co-simulation in the form of the Functional Mock-up Interface.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] The US National Science Foundation (NSF) has identified cyber-physical systems as a key area of research.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] Through its CPS Program, it awards "Frontier" projects that are large-scale projects ($5-7M each) meant to significantly move the CPS technology forward.
[src:digital-twin/cyber-physical-system] Starting in late 2006, the NSF and other United States federal agencies sponsored several workshops on cyber-physical systems.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] A **digital twin** is a computational model of an intended or actual real-world physical product, system, or process (a *physical twin*) that serves as a digital counterpart of it for purposes such as simulation, integration, testing, monitoring, and maintenance.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] By its strict definition, a digital twin is distinguished from an ordinary simulation in that it continuously uses real data from its physical counterpart to dynamically synchronize with the real system.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] A model that operates without data from its physical counterpart may also be described as a digital twin, but this is considered an overly broad and largely marketing-oriented interpretation of the concept.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] A digital twin is "a set of adaptive models that emulate the behaviour of a physical system in a virtual system getting real-time data to update itself along its life cycle.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Digital twins emerged through continual improvements in modeling and engineering.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] In the 2010s and 2020s, manufacturing industries began moving beyond digital product definition to extending the digital twin concept to the entire manufacturing process.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Doing so allows the benefits of virtualization to be extended to domains such as inventory management including lean manufacturing, machinery crash avoidance, tooling design, troubleshooting, and preventive maintenance.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Digital twinning therefore allows extended reality and spatial computing to be applied not just to the product itself but also to all of the business processes that contribute to its production.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] The first digital twin, although not labeled as such, came about at NASA during the 1960s as a means of modelling the Apollo missions.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] NASA used simulators to evaluate the failure of Apollo 13's oxygen tanks.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] The broader idea that became the digital twin concept was anticipated by David Gelernter's 1991 book *Mirror Worlds*.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] During the late 1990s, the emergence of digital cities provided early practical demonstrations of this concept at an urban scale.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Projects such as "Helsinki Arena 2000" (initiated in 1996) built interactive 3D virtual models of the physical city.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] The digital twin concept consists of three distinct parts: the physical object or process and its physical environment, the digital representation of the object or process, and the communication channel between the physical and virtual representations.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] The connections between the physical version and the digital version include information flows and data that includes physical sensor flows between the physical and virtual objects and environments.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] The communication connection is referred to as the digital thread.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] The International Council of Systems Engineers (INCOSE) maintains in its Systems Engineering Body of Knowledge (SEBoK) that: "A digital twin is a related yet distinct concept to digital engineering.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Digital twins are commonly divided into the three subtypes: *digital twin prototype* (DTP), *digital twin instance* (DTI), and *digital twin aggregate* (DTA).
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] The DTP consists of the designs, analyses, and processes that realize a physical product.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] The DTI is the digital twin of each individual instance of the product once it is manufactured.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] The DTI is linked with its physical counterpart for the remainder of the physical counterpart's life.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] The DTA is the aggregation of DTIs whose data and information can be used for interrogation about the physical product, prognostics, and learning.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] The specific information contained in the digital twins is driven by use cases.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] The digital twin is a logical construct, meaning that the actual data and information may be contained in other applications.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] For some types of digital twin, there is contention about whether the label truly applies.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] For example, LNS Research defines "digital twin" as any executable virtual model of a physical system.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Researchers at the National Physical Laboratory have contested this definition, arguing that this includes "plain" models that do not produce results equivalent to measured quantities or are not dynamically updated in accordance with those measurements.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] They argue that this overly broad definition risks causing potential users to view "digital twin" as a buzzword and become cynical toward the idea.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] The term has also been applied to large language models trained to mimic specific people.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Describing these as "digital twins" implies a level of comprehensive fidelity that they fail to live up to in practice, and can cause psychological harm to users who believe that the model preserves or replicates human identity.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] In 2019 Sheremetyevo International Airport started developing and implementation of a digital twin model aimed to forecast and plan all the airport operations.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] In the design phase, a Digital Twin Prototype (DTP) is often created before a physical product exists.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] This virtual model is used for extensive simulation to test design choices and manufacturing processes.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] For example, in virtual commissioning, a digital twin of a proposed production line can simulate its operation to identify bottlenecks, optimize the layout of machinery, and validate automation logic before any physical equipment is installed.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] During production, digital twins use data from sensors connected to manufacturing equipment via the Internet of Things (IoT) to monitor and optimize operations.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] A distinction is sometimes made between a Digital Shadow, where data flows one way from the physical asset to the digital model, and a true Digital Twin, where the data flow is bidirectional, allowing the twin to also send control commands back to the asset.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Applications in this phase include process monitoring and control, where sensors measuring force, temperature, vibration, or power consumption feed data to a digital twin to monitor a process in real time.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] In friction stir welding, for instance, force sensor data can indicate whether sufficient contact is being made between the tool and workpieces to ensure a quality weld.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] In machining, acoustic emission signals can be analyzed to differentiate a worn tool from a new one, allowing for automated quality control.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Another application is real-time quality inspection, where vision systems integrated with a digital twin can automatically inspect products for defects on the production line.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] These systems can process images to detect surface defects, such as cracks or porosity in a weld, or measure geometric dimensions to ensure they meet specifications.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] After a product is manufactured and in service, its digital twin continues to collect performance data, often referred to as a Digital Twin Instance (DTI).
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] This is particularly valuable for high-value industrial assets like jet engines, wind turbines, or industrial machinery.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] One key application is predictive maintenance, where the digital twin analyzes operational data (e.g., temperature, vibration) to predict when a component is likely to fail.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] For example, a gearbox twin can analyze vibration signals to detect the future breakage of a tooth.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] This allows maintenance to be scheduled proactively, reducing unplanned downtime and preventing catastrophic failures.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Another application is performance optimization.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] By aggregating data from a whole fleet of assets—a Digital Twin Aggregate (DTA)—manufacturers can understand how their products perform under different real-world conditions.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] This information can be used to provide operational guidance to users or to inform the design of future product generations, creating a closed feedback loop from the service phase back to the design phase.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Digital twins are transforming construction by creating dynamic digital replicas of physical assets.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] They support health monitoring, ergonomic risk assessment, and predictive maintenance of structures like bridges and historical buildings.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Applications also optimize building energy and carbon performance.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Case studies, such as Weihai Port, highlight their practical success.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Digital twins rely on robust system architectures and tailored, requirements-driven designs.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Advanced models like LSTM enable predictive capabilities, though challenges in integration and scaling remain.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Recent studies have emphasized their role in enabling real-time operational control of HVAC, lighting, shading, and renewable systems, contributing significantly to decarbonization strategies.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Layered system architectures typically comprising sensing, data processing, simulation, and visualization layers that support scalable and interoperable solutions for these applications.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Geographic digital twins have been popularised in urban planning practice, given the increasing appetite for digital technology in the Smart Cities movement.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] These digital twins are often proposed in the form of interactive platforms to capture and display real-time 3D and 4D spatial data in order to model urban environments (cities) and the data feeds within them.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Visualization technologies such as augmented reality (AR) systems are being used as both collaborative tools for design and planning in the built environment integrating data feeds from embedded sensors in cities and API services to form digital twins.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] For example, AR can be used to create augmented reality maps, buildings, and data feeds projected onto tabletops for collaborative viewing by built environment professionals.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] In the United Kingdom in November 2018, for example, the Centre for Digital Built Britain published *The Gemini Principles*, outlining principles to guide development of a "national digital twin".
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] One of the earliest examples of a working 'digital twin' was achieved in 1996 during construction of the Heathrow Express facilities at Heathrow Airport's Terminal 1.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Consultant Mott MacDonald and BIM pioneer Jonathan Ingram connected movement sensors in the cofferdam and boreholes to the digital object-model to display movements in the model.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] A digital grouting object was made to monitor the effects of pumping grout into the earth to stabilise ground movements.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Healthcare has been recognized as an industry being disrupted by the digital twin technology.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] The concept was originally proposed and first used in health care product or equipment prognostics.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] With a digital twin, it has been predicted that lives could be improved in terms of medical health, sports and education by taking a more data-driven approach to healthcare.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Personalized models for patients, continuously adjustable based on tracked health and lifestyle parameters could ultimately lead to a virtual patient, with detailed description of the healthy state of an individual and not only on previous records.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Furthermore, the digital twin could enable individual's records to be compared to the population in order to easier find patterns with great detail.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] The biggest benefit of the digital twin on the healthcare industry would be the fact that healthcare could be tailored to anticipate the responses of individual patients.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Digital twins have been expected not only to lead to better resolutions when defining the health of an individual but also change the expected image of a healthy person.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Previously, 'healthy' was seen as the absence of disease indications.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Now, 'healthy' patients can be compared to the rest of the population in order to really define healthy.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] However, the emergence of the digital twin in healthcare also may lead to inequality, as the technology might not be accessible for everyone by widening the gap between the rich and poor.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Furthermore, the digital twin will identify patterns in a population which may lead to discrimination.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] As of 2025, digital twin applications in healthcare have expanded to include real‑time AI‑driven patient monitoring systems, personalized surgical simulations, and predictive diagnostics using multimodal data (e.g. imaging + wearables).
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Digital twins in the automobile industry are implemented by using existing data in order to facilitate processes and reduce marginal costs.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Currently, automobile designers expand the existing physical materiality by incorporating software-based digital abilities.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] A specific example of digital twin technology in the automotive industry is where automotive engineers use digital twin technology in combination with the firm's analytical tool in order to analyze how a specific car is driven.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] In doing so, they can suggest incorporating new features in the car that can reduce car accidents on the road, which was previously not possible in such a short time frame.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Digital twins are increasingly employed in the renewable energy industry to monitor and optimize systems such as wind farms, solar installations, microgrids, and battery storage.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] These virtual models help operators simulate real-world conditions, forecast issues, and enhance operational efficiency in a low-risk environment.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Recent reviews emphasize that digital twins support advanced management strategies for microgrids, such as day-ahead scheduling and real-time coordination across renewable assets, enhancing grid resilience.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Systematic analysis further shows that combining digital twins with predictive analytics in smart energy systems can reduce energy consumption by up to 30%, thanks to optimized load balancing and proactive maintenance.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] A UK-based demonstrator project used a digital twin for voltage control simulations in a microgrid, showing a reduction of renewable curtailment by approximately 56% in typical operation.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Utilities and technology providers worldwide are now piloting twin platforms to anticipate turbine maintenance, improve battery storage usage, and simulate grid behavior under extreme or variable conditions, indicating a trend toward more automated and resilient energy systems.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Digital twin technology is used in heritage and archaeological contexts to anticipate heritage loss and ensuring that an accurate record exists for heritage assets at risk, and engaging with planners to anticipate the needs of the cultural heritage sector.
[src:digital-twin/digital-twin] Twins can also be drivers for tourism and urban heritage trails, where they can act as introductions to significant or iconic monuments, thereby using heritage to draw people into urban centres.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] The main appeal of predictive maintenance is to allow convenient scheduling of corrective maintenance, and to prevent unexpected equipment failures.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] By taking into account measurements of the state of the equipment, maintenance work can be better planned (spare parts, people, etc.) and what would have been "unplanned stops" are transformed to shorter and fewer "planned stops", thus increasing plant availability.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Other potential advantages include increased equipment lifetime, increased plant safety, fewer accidents with negative impact on environment, and optimized spare parts handling.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Predictive maintenance differs from preventive maintenance because it does take into account the current condition of equipment (with measurements), instead of average or expected life statistics, to predict when maintenance will be required.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Machine Learning approaches are adopted for the forecasting of its future states.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Some of the main components that are necessary for implementing predictive maintenance are data collection and preprocessing, early fault detection, fault detection, time to failure prediction, and maintenance scheduling and resource optimization.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Predictive maintenance has been considered one of the driving forces for improving productivity and a way to achieve just-in-time manufacturing.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Predictive maintenance evaluates the condition of equipment by performing periodic (offline) or continuous (online) equipment condition monitoring.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] The ultimate goal of the approach is to perform maintenance at a scheduled point in time when the maintenance activity is most cost-effective and before the equipment loses performance within a threshold.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] This results in a reduction in unplanned downtime costs because of failure, where costs can be in the hundreds of thousands per day depending on industry.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] In energy production, in addition to loss of revenue and component costs, fines can be levied for non-delivery, increasing costs even further.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] This is in contrast to time- and/or operation count-based maintenance, where a piece of equipment gets maintained whether it needs it or not.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Time-based maintenance is labor intensive, ineffective in identifying problems that develop between scheduled inspections, and therefore is not cost-effective.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] The "predictive" component of predictive maintenance stems from the goal of predicting the future trend of the equipment's condition.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] This approach uses principles of statistical process control to determine at what point in the future maintenance activities will be appropriate.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Most predictive inspections are performed while equipment is in service, thereby minimizing disruption of normal system operations.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Adoption of predictive maintenance can result in substantial cost savings and higher system reliability.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] In today's dynamic landscape of service maintenance, prolonged repair processes present a significant challenge for organizations striving to maintain operational excellence.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Extended downtime, increased Mean Time to Repair (MTTR), and production losses not only affect profitability but also disrupt service continuity and diminish customer satisfaction.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] As equipment ages and maintenance requirements intensify, the quest for innovative solutions becomes increasingly urgent.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] One goal is to transfer the predictive maintenance data to a computerized maintenance management system so that the equipment condition data is sent to the right equipment object to trigger maintenance planning, work order execution, and reporting.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Unless this is achieved, the predictive maintenance solution is of limited value, at least if the solution is implemented on a medium to large size plant with tens of thousands pieces of equipment.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] To evaluate equipment condition, predictive maintenance utilizes nondestructive testing technologies such as infrared, acoustic (partial discharge and airborne ultrasonic), corona detection, vibration analysis, sound level measurements, oil analysis, and other specific online tests.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] A new approach in this area is to utilize measurements on the actual equipment in combination with measurement of process performance, measured by other devices, to trigger equipment maintenance.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] This is primarily available in collaborative process automation systems (CPAS).
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Site measurements are often supported by wireless sensor networks to reduce the wiring cost.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Vibration analysis is most productive on high-speed rotating equipment and can be the most expensive component of a PdM program to get up and running.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Vibration analysis, when properly done, allows the user to evaluate the condition of equipment and avoid failures.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] The latest generation of vibration analyzers comprises more capabilities and automated functions than its predecessors.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Many units display the full vibration spectrum of three axes simultaneously, providing a snapshot of what is going on with a particular machine.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] But despite such capabilities, not even the most sophisticated equipment successfully predicts developing problems unless the operator understands and applies the basics of vibration analysis.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] In certain situations, strong background noise interferences from several competing sources may mask the signal of interest and hinder the industrial applicability of vibration sensors.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Consequently, motor current signature analysis (MCSA) is a non-intrusive alternative to vibration measurement which has the potential to monitor faults from both electrical and mechanical systems.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Remote visual inspection is the first non-destructive testing.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] It provides a cost-efficient primary assessment.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Essential information and defaults can be deduced from the external appearance of the piece, such as folds, breaks, cracks, and corrosion.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] The remote visual inspection has to be carried out in good conditions with a sufficient lighting (350 LUX at least).
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] When the part of the piece to be controlled is not directly accessible, an instrument made of mirrors and lenses called endoscope is used.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Hidden defects with external irregularities may indicate a more serious defect inside.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Acoustical analysis can be done on a sonic or ultrasonic level.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] New ultrasonic techniques for condition monitoring make it possible to "hear" friction and stress in rotating machinery, which can predict deterioration earlier than conventional techniques.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Ultrasonic technology is sensitive to high-frequency sounds that are inaudible to the human ear and distinguishes them from lower-frequency sounds and mechanical vibration.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Machine friction and stress waves produce distinctive sounds in the upper ultrasonic range.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Changes in these friction and stress waves can suggest deteriorating conditions much earlier than technologies such as vibration or oil analysis.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] With proper ultrasonic measurement and analysis, it's possible to differentiate normal wear from abnormal wear, physical damage, imbalance conditions, and lubrication problems based on a direct relationship between asset and operating conditions.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Sonic monitoring equipment is less expensive, but it also has fewer uses than ultrasonic technologies.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Sonic technology is useful only on mechanical equipment, while ultrasonic equipment can detect electrical problems and is more flexible and reliable in detecting mechanical problems.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Infrared monitoring and analysis has the widest range of application (from high- to low-speed equipment), and it can be effective for spotting both mechanical and electrical failures; some consider it to currently be the most cost-effective technology.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Oil analysis is a long-term program that, where relevant, can eventually be more predictive than any of the other technologies.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] It can take years for a plant's oil program to reach this level of sophistication and effectiveness.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Analytical techniques performed on oil samples can be classified in two categories: used oil analysis and wear particle analysis.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Used oil analysis determines the condition of the lubricant itself, determines the quality of the lubricant, and checks its suitability for continued use.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Wear particle analysis determines the mechanical condition of machine components that are lubricated.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Through wear particle analysis, you can identify the composition of the solid material present and evaluate particle type, size, concentration, distribution, and morphology.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Model-based condition monitoring is another approach used in predictive maintenance programs.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] It involves analyzing electrical signals, such as motor current and voltage, and comparing measured parameters to a reference model in order to identify deviations associated with faults.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] This method has been applied in aerospace and industrial systems.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Model-based systems can support automated data analysis and continuous monitoring.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] Additional predictive maintenance methods include various data-driven and smart testing strategies.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] An application of predictive maintenance is in the automotive and transportation sectors, particularly in fleet management.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] The process relies on telematics to collect real-time data from vehicles.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] A telematic control unit installed in a vehicle continuously gathers telemetry from the engine's CAN bus, including diagnostic trouble codes (DTCs), fuel consumption, and component status.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] This data is then transmitted to a fleet telematics system, where machine learning algorithms analyze it to detect patterns that precede failures.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] This allows the system to predict potential issues with critical components, such as the battery, starter motor, or brakes, before they result in a breakdown.
[src:digital-twin/predictive-maintenance] This approach is a component of modern fleet digitalization, enabling businesses to schedule maintenance at a cost-effective time, reduce unplanned downtime, and improve vehicle reliability.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] In industry, **product lifecycle management** (**PLM**) is the process of managing the entire lifecycle of a product from its inception through the engineering, design, and manufacture, as well as the service and disposal of manufactured products.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] PLM integrates people, data, processes, and business systems and provides a product information backbone for companies and their extended enterprises.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] The inspiration for the burgeoning business process now known as PLM came from American Motors Corporation (AMC).
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] The automaker was looking for a way to speed up its product development process to compete better against its larger competitors in 1985, according to François Castaing, Vice President for Product Engineering and Development.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] The first part in its quest for faster product development was computer-aided design (CAD) software system that made engineers more productive.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] The second part of this effort was the new communication system that allowed conflicts to be resolved faster, as well as reducing costly engineering changes because all drawings and documents were in a central database.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] The product data management was so effective that after Chrysler purchased AMC, the system was expanded throughout the enterprise connecting everyone involved in designing and building products.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] While an early adopter of PLM technology, Chrysler was able to become the auto industry's lowest-cost producer, recording development costs that were half of the industry average by the mid-1990s.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] PLM systems help organizations cope with the increasing complexity and engineering challenges of developing new products for the global competitive markets.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Product lifecycle management (PLM) should be distinguished from 'product life-cycle management (marketing)' (PLCM).
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] PLM describes a product's engineering aspect, from managing its descriptions and properties through its development and useful life.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] In contrast, PLCM refers to the commercial management of a product's life in the business market concerning costs and sales measures.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Product lifecycle management can be considered one of the four cornerstones of a manufacturing corporation's information technology structure.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] One form of PLM is called people-centric PLM.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] While traditional PLM tools have been deployed only on or during the release phase, people-centric PLM targets the design phase.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] This broader reach has resulted in the extension of PLM into closed-loop lifecycle management (CL2M).
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Product and portfolio management2 (PPM) are focused on managing resource allocation, tracking progress, planning for new product development projects that are in process (or in a holding status).
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Portfolio management is a tool that assists management in tracking progress on new products and making trade-off decisions when allocating scarce resources.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Product design (CAx) is the process of creating a new product to be sold by a business to its customers.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Manufacturing process management (MPM) is a collection of technologies and methods used to define how products are to be manufactured.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Product data management (PDM) is focused on capturing and maintaining information on products and/or services through their development and useful life.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Change management is an important part of PDM/PLM.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] The core of PLM (product lifecycle management) is the creation and central management of all product data and the technology used to access this information and knowledge.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] PLM as a discipline emerged from tools such as CAD, CAM and PDM, but can be viewed as the integration of these tools with methods, people and the processes through all stages of a product's life.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] It is not just about software technology but is also a business strategy.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] For simplicity, the stages described are shown in a traditional sequential engineering workflow.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] The reality is however more complex, people and departments cannot perform their tasks in isolation and one activity cannot simply finish, and the next activity start.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Design is an iterative process, often designs need to be modified due to manufacturing constraints or conflicting requirements.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Whether a customer order fits into the timeline depends on the industry type and whether the products are, for example, built to order, engineered to order, or assembled to order.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Many software solutions have been developed to organize and integrate the different phases of a product's lifecycle.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] PLM should not be considered as a single software product, but as a collection of software tools and working methods integrated to address single stages of the lifecycle, connect different tasks, or manage the whole process.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Some software providers cover the whole PLM range, while others have a single niche application.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Some applications can span many fields of PLM with different modules within the same data model.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] An overview of the fields within PLM is covered here.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] The simple classifications do not always fit exactly; many areas overlap, and many software products cover more than one area or do not fit easily into one category.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] One of the main goals of PLM is to collect knowledge that can be reused for other projects and to coordinate the simultaneous concurrent development of many products.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] It is about business processes, people, and methods as much as software application solutions.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Although PLM is mainly associated with engineering tasks, it also involves marketing activities such as product portfolio management (PPM), particularly concerning new product development (NPD).
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Each industry has several life-cycle models to consider, but most are relatively similar.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] The first stage is the definition of the product requirements based on customer, company, market, and regulatory bodies' viewpoints.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] From this specification, the product's major technical parameters can be defined.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] In parallel, the initial concept design work is performed, defining the aesthetics of the product together with its main functional aspects.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Many different media are used for these processes, from pencil and paper to clay models to 3D CAID computer-aided industrial design software.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] In some concepts, the investment of resources into research or analysis of options may be included in the conception phase – e.g., bringing the technology to a level of maturity sufficient to move to the next phase.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] However, life-cycle engineering is iterative.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] It is always possible that something does not work well in any phase enough to back up into a prior phase – perhaps back to conception or research.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] The new product development process phase collects and evaluates market and technical risks by measuring the KPI and scoring model.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] This step is where the detailed design and development of the product's form starts, progressing to prototype testing, from pilot release to full product launch.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] It can also involve redesign and ramping to improve existing products and planned obsolescence.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] CAD is the primary tool used for design and development.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] This can be simple 2D drawing/drafting or 3D parametric feature-based solid/surface modeling.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Such software may include Hybrid Modeling, Reverse Engineering, KBE (knowledge-based engineering), NDT (Nondestructive testing), and Assembly construction.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] This step covers many engineering disciplines, including mechanical, electrical, electronic, software (embedded), and domain-specific, such as architectural, aerospace, and automotive.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Along with creating geometry, the components and product assemblies are analyzed.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Simulation, validation, and optimization tasks are carried out using CAE (computer-aided engineering) software, either integrated into the CAD package or stand-alone.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] These are used to perform tasks such as Stress analysis, FEA (finite element analysis), kinematics, computational fluid dynamics (CFD), and mechanical event simulation (MES).
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] CAQ (computer-aided quality) is used for tasks such as Dimensional tolerance (engineering) analysis.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Another task performed at this stage is sourcing bought-out components, possibly with the aid of procurement systems.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Once the design of the product's components is complete, the method of manufacturing is defined.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] This includes CAD tasks such as tool design; including the creation of CNC machining instructions for the product's parts as well as the creation of specific tools to manufacture those parts, using integrated or separate CAM (computer-aided manufacturing) software.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] This will also involve analysis tools for process simulation of operations such as casting, molding, and die-press forming.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Once the manufacturing method has been identified, CPM comes into play.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] This involves CAPE (computer-aided production engineering) or CAP/CAPP (computer-aided production planning) tools for carrying out factory, plant and facility layout, and production simulation e.g. press-line simulation, industrial ergonomics, as well as tool selection management.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] After components are manufactured, their geometrical form and size can be checked against the original CAD data with the use of computer-aided inspection equipment and software.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Parallel to the engineering tasks, sales product configuration, and marketing documentation work takes place.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] This could include transferring engineering data (geometry and part list data) to a web-based sales configurator and other desktop publishing systems.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Another phase of the lifecycle involves managing "in-service" information.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] This can include providing customers and service engineers with the support and information required for repair and maintenance, as well as waste management or recycling.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] This can involve the use of tools such as Maintenance, Repair, and Overhaul Management (MRO) software.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] An effective service consideration begins during and even prior to product design as an integral part of product lifecycle management.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Service Lifecycle Management (SLM) has critical touchpoints at all phases of the product lifecycle that must be considered.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Connecting and enriching a common digital thread will provide enhanced visibility across functions, improve data quality, and minimize costly delays and rework.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] There is an end-of-life to every product.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Whether it be the disposal or destruction of material objects or information, this needs to be carefully considered since it may be legislated and hence not free from ramifications.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] This modernization approach often extends the product lifecycle and delays end-of-life disposal.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] None of the above phases should be considered as isolated.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] In reality, a project does not run sequentially or separated from other product development projects, with information flowing between different people and systems.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] A major part of PLM is the coordination and management of product definition data.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] This includes managing engineering changes and release status of components; configuration product variations; document management; planning project resources as well as timescale and risk assessment.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] For these tasks data of a graphical, textual, and meta nature – such as product bills of materials (BOMs) – needs to be managed.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] These systems may also be linked to other corporate systems such as SCM, CRM, and ERP.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Associated with these systems are project management systems for project/program planning.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] This central role is covered by numerous collaborative product development tools that run throughout the whole lifecycle and across organizations.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] This requires many technology tools in the areas of conferencing, data sharing, and data translation.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] This specialized field is referred to as product visualization which includes technologies such as DMU (digital mock-up), immersive virtual digital prototyping (virtual reality), and photo-realistic imaging.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] The broad array of solutions that make up the tools used within a PLM solution-set (e.g., CAD, CAM, CAx) were initially used by dedicated practitioners who invested time and effort to gain the required skills.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Designers and engineers produced excellent results with CAD systems, manufacturing engineers became highly skilled CAM users, while analysts, administrators, and managers fully mastered their support technologies.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] However, achieving the full advantages of PLM requires the participation of many people of various skills from throughout an extended enterprise, each requiring the ability to access and operate on the inputs and output of other participants.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Despite the increased ease of use of PLM tools, cross-training all personnel on the entire PLM tool-set has not proven to be practical.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Now, however, advances are being made to address ease of use for all participants within the PLM arena.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] One such advance is the availability of "role" specific user interfaces.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Through tailorable user interfaces (UIs), the commands that are presented to users are appropriate to their function and expertise.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Feature-based CAD systems have allowed simultaneous work on the 3D solid model and the 2D drawing by means of two separate files, with the drawing looking at the data in the model; when the model changes the drawing will associatively update.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Some CAD packages also allow associative copying of geometry between files.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] This allows, for example, the copying of a part design into the files used by the tooling designer.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] The manufacturing engineer can then start work on tools before the final design freeze; when a design changes size or shape the tool geometry will then update.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Concurrent engineering also has the added benefit of providing better and more immediate communication between departments, reducing the chance of costly, late design changes.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] It adopts a problem-prevention method as compared to the problem-solving and re-designing method of traditional sequential engineering.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Bottom-up design (CAD-centric) occurs where the definition of 3D models of a product starts with the construction of individual components.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] These are then virtually brought together in sub-assemblies of more than one level until the full product is digitally defined.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] This is sometimes known as the "review structure" which shows what the product will look like.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Bottom-up design tends to focus on the capabilities of available real-world physical technology, implementing those solutions to which this technology is most suited.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] When these bottom-up solutions have real-world value, bottom-up design can be much more efficient than top-down design.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] The risk of bottom-up design is that it very efficiently provides solutions to low-value problems.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Top-down design is focused on high-level functional requirements, with relatively less focus on existing implementation technology.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] A top-level spec is repeatedly decomposed into lower-level structures and specifications until the physical implementation layer is reached.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] The positive value of top-down design is that it preserves a focus on the optimum solution requirements.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] A part-centric top-down design may eliminate some of the risks of top-down design.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] This starts with a layout model, often a simple 2D sketch defining basic sizes and some major defining parameters, which may include some industrial design elements.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Geometry from this is associatively copied down to the next level, which represents different subsystems of the product.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] The geometry in the sub-systems is then used to define more detail in the levels below.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Depending on the complexity of the product, a number of levels of this assembly are created until the basic definition of components can be identified, such as position and principal dimensions.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] This information is then associatively copied to component files.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] In these files the components are detailed; this is where the classic bottom-up assembly starts.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] The top-down assembly is sometimes known as a "control structure".
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] If a single file is used to define the layout and parameters for the review structure it is often known as a skeleton file.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Defense engineering traditionally develops the product structure from the top down.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] The system engineering process prescribes a functional decomposition of requirements and then the physical allocation of product structure to the functions.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] This top down approach would normally have lower levels of the product structure developed from CAD data as a bottom-up structure or design.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Both-ends-against-the-middle (BEATM) design is a design process that endeavors to combine the best features of top-down design, and bottom-up design into one process.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] A BEATM design process flow may begin with an emergent technology that suggests solutions that may have value, or it may begin with a top-down view of an important problem that needs a solution.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] In either case, the key attribute of BEATM design methodology is to immediately focus on both ends of the design process flow: a top-down view of the solution requirements, and a bottom-up view of the available technology which may offer the promise of an efficient solution.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] The BEATM design process proceeds from both ends in search of an optimum merging somewhere between the top-down requirements, and bottom-up efficient implementation.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] In this fashion, BEATM has been shown to genuinely offer the best of both methodologies.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Indeed, some of the best success stories from either top-down or bottom-up have been successful because of an intuitive, yet unconscious use of the BEATM methodology.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] When employed consciously, BEATM offers even more powerful advantages.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Front loading is taking top-down design to the next stage.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] The complete control structure and review structure, as well as downstream data such as drawings, tooling development, and CAM models, are constructed before the product has been defined or a project kick-off has been authorized.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] These assemblies of files constitute a template from which a family of products can be constructed.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] When the decision has been made to go with a new product, the parameters of the product are entered into the template model, and all the associated data is updated.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Obviously, predefined associative models will not be able to predict all possibilities and will require additional work.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] The main principle is that a lot of the experimental/investigative work has already been completed.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] A lot of knowledge is built into these templates to be reused on new products.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] This does require additional resources "up front" but can drastically reduce the time between project kick-off and launch.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Such methods do however require organizational changes, as considerable engineering efforts are moved into "offline" development departments.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] It can be seen as an analogy to creating a concept car to test new technology for future products, but in this case, the work is directly used for the next product generation.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Individual components cannot be constructed in isolation.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] CAD and CAID models of components are created within the context of some or all of the other components within the product being developed.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] This is achieved using assembly modelling techniques.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] The geometry of other components can be seen and referenced within the CAD tool being used.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] The other referenced components may or may not have been created using the same CAD tool, with their geometry being translated from other collaborative product development (CPD) formats.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Some assembly checking such as DMU is also carried out using product visualization software.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Product and process lifecycle management **(PPLM)** is an alternate genre of PLM in which the process by which the product is made is just as important as the product itself.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Typically, this is the life sciences and advanced specialty chemicals markets.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] The process behind the manufacture of a given compound is a key element of the regulatory filing for a new drug application.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] As such, PPLM seeks to manage information around the development of the process in a similar fashion that baseline PLM talks about managing information around the development of the product.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] One variant of PPLM implementations are Process Development Execution Systems (PDES).
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] They typically implement the whole development cycle of high-tech manufacturing technology developments, from initial conception, through development, and into manufacture.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] PDES integrates people with different backgrounds from potentially different legal entities, data, information and knowledge, and business processes.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] After the Great Recession, PLM investments from 2010 onwards showed a higher growth rate than most general IT spending.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] Total spending on PLM software and services was estimated in 2020 to be $26 billion a year, with an estimated compound annual growth rate of 7.2% from 2021 to 2028.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] This was expected to be driven by a demand for software solutions for management functions, such as change, cost, compliance, data, and governance management.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] The relation between these five objects can be presented as a pyramid with its tip associated with the lowest Cost, highest Productivity, highest Quality, most Flexibility, and greatest Sustainability.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] The points inside of this pyramid are associated with different combinations of five criteria.
[src:digital-twin/product-lifecycle] The tip of the pyramid represents an ideal (but likely highly unfeasible) system whereas the base of the pyramid represents the worst system possible.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] A **simulation** is an imitative representation of a process or system that could exist in the real world.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] In this broad sense, simulation can often be used interchangeably with model.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Sometimes a clear distinction between the two terms is made, in which simulations require the use of models; the model represents the key characteristics or behaviors of the selected system or process, whereas the simulation represents the evolution of the model over time.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Another way to distinguish between the terms is to define simulation as experimentation with the help of a model.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] This definition includes time-independent simulations.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Often, computers are used to execute the simulation.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Simulation is used in many contexts, such as simulation of technology for performance tuning or optimizing, safety engineering, testing, training, education, and video games.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Simulation is also used with scientific modelling of natural systems or human systems to gain insight into their functioning, as in economics.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Simulation can be used to show the eventual real effects of alternative conditions and courses of action.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Simulation is also used when the real system cannot be engaged, because it may not be accessible, or it may be dangerous or unacceptable to engage, or it is being designed but not yet built, or it may simply not exist.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Procedures and protocols for model verification and validation are an ongoing field of academic study, refinement, research and development in simulations technology or practice, particularly in the work of computer simulation.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Historically, simulations used in different fields developed largely independently, but 20th-century studies of systems theory and cybernetics combined with the spreading use of computers across all those fields have led to some unification and a more systematic view of the concept.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] A *stand-alone simulation* is a simulation running on a single workstation by itself.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] A **distributed simulation** is one which uses more than one computer simultaneously, to guarantee access from/to different resources (e.g. multi-users operating different systems, or distributed data sets); a classical example is Distributed Interactive Simulation (DIS).
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] A *synthetic environment* is a computer simulation that can be included in human-in-the-loop simulations.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Data simulation creates artificial data to replicate the behavior of real-world data.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] The artificial data is generated using computer models or programs based on specific rules, patterns, or characteristics.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] This type of data is designed to imitate the operations of real systems, processes, or behaviors, enabling researchers and analysts to study and test scenarios without directly observing or collecting information from the real world.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] A computer simulation (or "sim") is an attempt to model a real-life or hypothetical situation on a computer so that it can be studied to see how the system works.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] By changing variables in the simulation, predictions may be made about the behaviour of the system.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] It is a tool to virtually investigate the behaviour of the system under study.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Computer simulation has become a useful part of modeling many natural systems in physics, chemistry and biology, and human systems in economics and social science (e.g., computational sociology) as well as in engineering to gain insight into the operation of those systems.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] A good example of the usefulness of using computers to simulate can be found in the field of network traffic simulation.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] In such simulations, the model behaviour will change each simulation according to the set of initial parameters assumed for the environment.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Traditionally, the formal modeling of systems has been via a mathematical model, which attempts to find analytical solutions enabling the prediction of the behaviour of the system from a set of parameters and initial conditions.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Computer simulation is often used as an adjunct to, or substitution for, modeling systems for which simple closed form analytic solutions are not possible.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] There are many different types of computer simulation, the common feature they all share is the attempt to generate a sample of representative scenarios for a model in which a complete enumeration of all possible states would be prohibitive or impossible.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Several software packages exist for running computer-based simulation modeling (e.g.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Monte Carlo simulation, stochastic modeling, multimethod modeling) that makes all the modeling almost effortless.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Modern usage of the term "computer simulation" may encompass virtually any computer-based representation.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] The computer simulates the subject machine.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Accordingly, in theoretical computer science the term *simulation* is a relation between state transition systems, useful in the study of operational semantics.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Less theoretically, an interesting application of computer simulation is to simulate computers using computers.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] For example, simulators have been used to debug a microprogram or sometimes commercial application programs, before the program is downloaded to the target machine.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Since the operation of the computer is simulated, all of the information about the computer's operation is directly available to the programmer, and the speed and execution of the simulation can be varied at will.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Simulators may also be used to interpret fault trees, or test VLSI logic designs before they are constructed.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Symbolic simulation uses variables to stand for unknown values.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] In the field of optimization, simulations of physical processes are often used in conjunction with evolutionary computation to optimize control strategies.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Simulation is extensively used for educational purposes.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] It is used for cases where it is prohibitively expensive or simply too dangerous to allow trainees to use the real equipment in the real world.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] In such situations they will spend time learning valuable lessons in a "safe" virtual environment yet living a lifelike experience (or at least it is the goal).
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Often the convenience is to permit mistakes during training for a safety-critical system.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Simulations in education are somewhat like training simulations.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] The term 'microworld' is used to refer to educational simulations which model some abstract concept rather than simulating a realistic object or environment, or in some cases model a real-world environment in a simplistic way so as to help a learner develop an understanding of the key concepts.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Normally, a user can create some sort of construction within the microworld that will behave in a way consistent with the concepts being modeled.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Seymour Papert was one of the first to advocate the value of microworlds, and the Logo programming environment developed by Papert is one of the most well-known microworlds.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Project management simulation is increasingly used to train students and professionals in the art and science of project management.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Using simulation for project management training improves learning retention and enhances the learning process.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] In recent years, there has been increasing use of social simulations for staff training in aid and development agencies.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] The Carana simulation, for example, was first developed by the United Nations Development Programme, and is now used in a very revised form by the World Bank for training staff to deal with fragile and conflict-affected countries.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Military uses for simulation often involve aircraft or armoured fighting vehicles, but can also target small arms and other weapon systems training.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Specifically, virtual firearms ranges have become the norm in most military training processes and there is a significant amount of data to suggest this is a useful tool for armed professionals.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] A **virtual simulation** is a category of simulation that uses simulation equipment to create a **simulated world** for the user.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Virtual simulations allow users to interact with a virtual world.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Virtual worlds operate on platforms of integrated software and hardware components.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] In this manner, the system can accept input from the user (e.g., body tracking, voice/sound recognition, physical controllers) and produce output to the user (e.g., visual display, aural display, haptic display) .
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Virtual simulations use the aforementioned modes of interaction to produce a sense of immersion for the user.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] There is a wide variety of input hardware available to accept user input for virtual simulations.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Research in future input systems holds a great deal of promise for virtual simulations.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Systems such as brain–computer interfaces (BCIs) offer the ability to further increase the level of immersion for virtual simulation users.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Lee, Keinrath, Scherer, Bischof, Pfurtscheller proved that naïve subjects could be trained to use a BCI to navigate a virtual apartment with relative ease.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Using the BCI, the authors found that subjects were able to freely navigate the virtual environment with relatively minimal effort.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] It is possible that these types of systems will become standard input modalities in future virtual simulation systems.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] There is a wide variety of output hardware available to deliver stimuli to users in virtual simulations.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Many medical simulators involve a computer connected to a plastic simulation of the relevant anatomy.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Sophisticated simulators of this type employ a life-size mannequin that responds to injected drugs and can be programmed to create simulations of life-threatening emergencies.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] In other simulations, visual components of the procedure are reproduced by computer graphics techniques, while touch-based components are reproduced by haptic feedback devices combined with physical simulation routines computed in response to the user's actions.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Medical simulations of this sort will often use 3D CT or MRI scans of patient data to enhance realism.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Some medical simulations are developed to be widely distributed (such as web-enabled simulations and procedural simulations that can be viewed via standard web browsers) and can be interacted with using standard computer interfaces, such as the keyboard and mouse.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] An important medical application of a simulator—although, perhaps, denoting a slightly different meaning of *simulator*—is the use of a placebo drug, a formulation that simulates the active drug in trials of drug efficacy.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Patient safety is a concern in the medical industry.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Patients have been known to suffer injuries and even death due to management error, and lack of using best standards of care and training.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Simulation is being used to study patient safety, as well as train medical professionals.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Studying patient safety and safety interventions in healthcare is challenging, because there is a lack of experimental control (i.e., patient complexity, system/process variances) to see if an intervention made a meaningful difference (Groves & Manges, 2017).
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] An example of innovative simulation to study patient safety is from nursing research.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] (2016) used a high-fidelity simulation to examine nursing safety-oriented behaviors during times such as change-of-shift report.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] However, the value of simulation interventions to translating to clinical practice are is still debatable.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] As Nishisaki states, "there is good evidence that simulation training improves provider and team self-efficacy and competence on manikins.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] There is also good evidence that procedural simulation improves actual operational performance in clinical settings." However, there is a need to have improved evidence to show that crew resource management training through simulation.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] One of the largest challenges is showing that team simulation improves team operational performance at the bedside.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Although evidence that simulation-based training actually improves patient outcome has been slow to accrue, today the ability of simulation to provide hands-on experience that translates to the operating room is no longer in doubt.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] One of the largest factors that might impact the ability to have training impact the work of practitioners at the bedside is the ability to empower frontline staff (Stewart, Manges, Ward, 2015).
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Another example of an attempt to improve patient safety through the use of simulations training is patient care to deliver just-in-time service or/and just-in-place.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] This training consists of 20 minutes of simulated training just before workers report to shift.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] One study found that just in time training improved the transition to the bedside.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] The conclusion as reported in Nishisaki (2008) work, was that the simulation training improved resident participation in real cases; but did not sacrifice the quality of service.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] It could be therefore hypothesized that by increasing the number of highly trained residents through the use of simulation training, that the simulation training does, in fact, increase patient safety.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] The first medical simulators were simple models of human patients.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Since antiquity, these representations in clay and stone were used to demonstrate clinical features of disease states and their effects on humans.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Models have been found in many cultures and continents.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] These models have been used in some cultures (e.g., Chinese culture) as a "diagnostic" instrument, allowing women to consult male physicians while maintaining social laws of modesty.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Models are used today to help students learn the anatomy of the musculoskeletal system and organ systems.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] The need for a "uniform mechanism to educate, evaluate, and certify simulation instructors for the health care profession" was recognized by McGaghie et al. in their critical review of simulation-based medical education research.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] In 2012 the SSH piloted two new certifications to provide recognition to educators in an effort to meet this need.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Active models that attempt to reproduce living anatomy or physiology are recent developments.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] The famous "Harvey" mannequin was developed at the University of Miami and is able to recreate many of the physical findings of the cardiology examination, including palpation, auscultation, and electrocardiography.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] More recently, interactive models have been developed that respond to actions taken by a student or physician.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Until recently, these simulations were two dimensional computer programs that acted more like a textbook than a patient.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Computer simulations have the advantage of allowing a student to make judgments, and also to make errors.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] The process of iterative learning through assessment, evaluation, decision making, and error correction creates a much stronger learning environment than passive instruction.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Simulators have been proposed as an ideal tool for assessment of students for clinical skills.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] For patients, "cybertherapy" can be used for sessions simulating traumatic experiences, from fear of heights to social anxiety.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Programmed patients and simulated clinical situations, including mock disaster drills, have been used extensively for education and evaluation.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] These "lifelike" simulations are expensive, and lack reproducibility.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] A fully functional "3Di" simulator would be the most specific tool available for teaching and measurement of clinical skills.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Gaming platforms have been applied to create these virtual medical environments to create an interactive method for learning and application of information in a clinical context.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Immersive disease state simulations allow a doctor or HCP to experience what a disease actually feels like.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Using sensors and transducers, symptomatic effects can be delivered to a participant, allowing them to experience the patient’s disease state.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Such a simulator meets the goals of an objective and standardized examination for clinical competence.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] This system is superior to examinations that use "standard patients" because it permits the quantitative measurement of competence, as well as reproducing the same objective findings.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] The first simulation game may have been created as early as 1947 by Thomas T.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] This was a straightforward game that simulated a missile being fired at a target.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] The curve of the missile and its speed could be adjusted using several knobs.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] In 1958, a computer game called *Tennis for Two* was created by Willy Higginbotham which simulated a tennis game between two players who could both play at the same time using hand controls and was displayed on an oscilloscope.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] This was one of the first electronic video games to use a graphical display.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Computer-generated imagery was used in the film to simulate objects as early as 1972 in *A Computer Animated Hand*, parts of which were shown on the big screen in the 1976 film *Futureworld*.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] This was followed by the "targeting computer" that young Skywalker turns off in the 1977 film *Star Wars*.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] The film *Tron* (1982) was the first film to use computer-generated imagery for more than a couple of minutes.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Advances in technology in the 1980s caused 3D simulation to become more widely used and it began to appear in movies and in computer-based games such as Atari's *Battlezone* (1980) and Acornsoft's *Elite* (1984), one of the first wire-frame 3D graphics games for home computers.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Advances in technology in the 1980s made the computer more affordable and more capable than they were in previous decades, which facilitated the rise of computer such as the Xbox gaming.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] The first video game consoles released in the 1970s and early 1980s fell prey to the industry crash in 1983, but in 1985, Nintendo released the Nintendo Entertainment System (NES) which became one of the best selling consoles in video game history.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] In the 1990s, computer games became widely popular with the release of such game as *The Sims* and *Command & Conquer* and the still increasing power of desktop computers.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Today, computer simulation games such as *World of Warcraft* are played by millions of people around the world.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] In 1993, the film *Jurassic Park* became the first popular film to use computer-generated graphics extensively, integrating the simulated dinosaurs almost seamlessly into live action scenes.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] This event transformed the film industry; in 1995, the film *Toy Story* was the first film to use only computer-generated images and by the new millennium computer generated graphics were the leading choice for special effects in films.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] The advent of virtual cinematography in the early 2000s has led to an explosion of movies that would have been impossible to shoot without it.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Classic examples are the digital look-alikes of Neo, Smith and other characters in the *Matrix* sequels and the extensive use of physically impossible camera runs in *The Lord of the Rings* trilogy.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Computer-generated imagery is "the application of the field of 3D computer graphics to special effects".
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] This technology is used for visual effects because they are high in quality, controllable, and can create effects that would not be feasible using any other technology either because of cost, resources or safety.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Computer-generated graphics can be seen in many live-action movies today, especially those of the action genre.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Further, computer-generated imagery has almost completely supplanted hand-drawn animation in children's movies which are increasingly computer-generated only.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Examples of movies that use computer-generated imagery include *Finding Nemo*, *300* and *Iron Man*.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Simulation games, as opposed to other genres of video and computer games, represent or simulate an environment accurately.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Moreover, they represent the interactions between the playable characters and the environment realistically.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] These kinds of games are usually more complex in terms of gameplay.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Simulation games have become incredibly popular among people of all ages.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Popular simulation games include *SimCity* and *Tiger Woods PGA Tour*.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] There are also flight simulator and driving simulator games.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Simulators have been used for entertainment since the Link Trainer in the 1930s.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] The first modern simulator ride to open at a theme park was Disney's Star Tours in 1987 soon followed by Universal's The Funtastic World of Hanna-Barbera in 1990 which was the first ride to be done entirely with computer graphics.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Simulator rides are the progeny of military training simulators and commercial simulators, but they are different in a fundamental way.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] While military training simulators react realistically to the input of the trainee in real time, ride simulators only feel like they move realistically and move according to prerecorded motion scripts.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] One of the first simulator rides, Star Tours, which cost $32 million, used a hydraulic motion based cabin.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] The movement was programmed by a joystick.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Today's simulator rides, such as The Amazing Adventures of Spider-Man include elements to increase the amount of immersion experienced by the riders such as: 3D imagery, physical effects (spraying water or producing scents), and movement through an environment.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p01] Another important goal of simulation in manufacturing systems is to quantify system performance.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] An automobile simulator provides an opportunity to reproduce the characteristics of real vehicles in a virtual environment.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] It replicates the external factors and conditions with which a vehicle interacts enabling a driver to feel as if they are sitting in the cab of their own vehicle.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Scenarios and events are replicated with sufficient reality to ensure that drivers become fully immersed in the experience rather than simply viewing it as an educational experience.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] The simulator provides a constructive experience for the novice driver and enables more complex exercises to be undertaken by the more mature driver.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] For novice drivers, truck simulators provide an opportunity to begin their career by applying best practice.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] For mature drivers, simulation provides the ability to enhance good driving or to detect poor practice and to suggest the necessary steps for remedial action.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] For companies, it provides an opportunity to educate staff in the driving skills that achieve reduced maintenance costs, improved productivity and, most importantly, to ensure the safety of their actions in all possible situations.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] A **biomechanics simulator** is a simulation platform for creating dynamic mechanical models built from combinations of rigid and deformable bodies, joints, constraints, and various force actuators.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] It is specialized for creating biomechanical models of human anatomical structures, with the intention to study their function and eventually assist in the design and planning of medical treatment.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] A biomechanics simulator is used to analyze walking dynamics, study sports performance, simulate surgical procedures, analyze joint loads, design medical devices, and animate human and animal movement.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] A neuromechanical simulator combines biomechanical and biologically realistic neural network simulation.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] It allows the user to test hypotheses about the neural basis of behavior in a physically accurate 3D virtual environment.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] A city simulator can be a city-building game but can also be a tool used by urban planners to understand how cities are likely to evolve in response to various policy decisions.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] AnyLogic is an example of modern, large-scale urban simulators designed for use by urban planners.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] City simulators are generally agent-based simulations with explicit representations for land use and transportation.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] UrbanSim and LEAM are examples of large-scale urban simulation models that are used by metropolitan planning agencies and military bases for land use and transportation planning.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Several Christmas-themed simulations exist, many of which are centered around Santa Claus.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] An example of these simulations are websites which claim to allow the user to track Santa Claus.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Another example of these simulations are websites that claim to allow the user to email or send messages to Santa Claus.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Websites such as emailSanta.com or Santa's former page on the now-defunct Windows Live Spaces by Microsoft use automated programs or scripts to generate personalized replies claimed to be from Santa himself based on user input.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Modern satellite communications systems (SATCOM) are often large and complex with many interacting parts and elements.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] In addition, the need for broadband connectivity on a moving vehicle has increased dramatically in the past few years for both commercial and military applications.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] To accurately predict and deliver high quality of service, SATCOM system designers have to factor in terrain as well as atmospheric and meteorological conditions in their planning.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] To deal with such complexity, system designers and operators increasingly turn towards computer models of their systems to simulate real-world operating conditions and gain insights into usability and requirements prior to final product sign-off.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Modeling improves the understanding of the system by enabling the SATCOM system designer or planner to simulate real-world performance by injecting the models with multiple hypothetical atmospheric and environmental conditions.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Simulation is often used in the training of civilian and military personnel.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] This usually occurs when it is prohibitively expensive or simply too dangerous to allow trainees to use the real equipment in the real world.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] In such situations, they will spend time learning valuable lessons in a "safe" virtual environment yet living a lifelike experience (or at least it is the goal).
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Simulation solutions are being increasingly integrated with computer-aided solutions and processes (computer-aided design or CAD, computer-aided manufacturing or CAM, computer-aided engineering or CAE, etc.).
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] The use of simulation throughout the product lifecycle, especially at the earlier concept and design stages, has the potential of providing substantial benefits.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] These benefits range from direct cost issues such as reduced prototyping and shorter time-to-market to better performing products and higher margins.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] However, for some companies, simulation has not provided the expected benefits.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] The successful use of simulation, early in the lifecycle, has been largely driven by increased integration of simulation tools with the entire set of CAD, CAM and product-lifecycle management solutions.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Simulation solutions can now function across the extended enterprise in a multi-CAD environment, and include solutions for managing simulation data and processes and ensuring that simulation results are made part of the product lifecycle history.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Simulation training has become a method for preparing people for disasters.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Simulations can replicate emergency situations and track how learners respond thanks to a lifelike experience.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Disaster preparedness simulations can involve training on how to handle terrorism attacks, natural disasters, pandemic outbreaks, or other life-threatening emergencies.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] One organization that has used simulation training for disaster preparedness is CADE (Center for Advancement of Distance Education).
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] CADE has used a video game to prepare emergency workers for multiple types of attacks.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] The Emergency Simulation Program (ESP) at the British Columbia Institute of Technology (BCIT), Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada is another example of an organization that uses simulation to train for emergency situations.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] At the University of Québec in Chicoutimi, a research team at the outdoor research and expertise laboratory (Laboratoire d'Expertise et de Recherche en Plein Air – LERPA) specializes in using wilderness backcountry accident simulations to verify emergency response coordination.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Instructionally, the benefits of emergency training through simulations are that learner performance can be tracked through the system.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] This allows the developer to make adjustments as necessary or alert the educator on topics that may require additional attention.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Other advantages are that the learner can be guided or trained on how to respond appropriately before continuing to the next emergency segment—this is an aspect that may not be available in the live environment.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Some emergency training simulators also allow for immediate feedback, while other simulations may provide a summary and instruct the learner to engage in the learning topic again.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] In a live-emergency situation, emergency responders do not have time to waste.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Simulation-training in this environment provides an opportunity for learners to gather as much information as they can and practice their knowledge in a safe environment.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] They can make mistakes without risk of endangering lives and be given the opportunity to correct their errors to prepare for the real-life emergency.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Simulation is an important feature in engineering systems or any system that involves many processes.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] For example, in electrical engineering, delay lines may be used to simulate propagation delay and phase shift caused by an actual transmission line.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Similarly, dummy loads may be used to simulate impedance without simulating propagation and is used in situations where propagation is unwanted.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] A simulator may imitate only a few of the operations and functions of the unit it simulates.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Most engineering simulations entail mathematical modeling and computer-assisted investigation.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] There are many cases, however, where mathematical modeling is not reliable.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Simulation of fluid dynamics problems often require both mathematical and physical simulations.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] In these cases the physical models require dynamic similitude.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Physical and chemical simulations have also direct realistic uses, rather than research uses; in chemical engineering, for example, process simulations are used to give the process parameters immediately used for operating chemical plants, such as oil refineries.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Simulators are also used for plant operator training.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] It is called Operator Training Simulator (OTS) and has been widely adopted by many industries from chemical to oil&gas and to the power industry.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] This created a safe and realistic virtual environment to train board operators and engineers.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Mimic is capable of providing high fidelity dynamic models of nearly all chemical plants for operator training and control system testing.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Software tools typically calculate biomechanical properties including individual muscle forces, joint forces and moments.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Most of these tools employ standard ergonomic evaluation methods such as the NIOSH lifting equation and Rapid Upper Limb Assessment (RULA).
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Some simulations also analyze physiological measures including metabolism, energy expenditure, and fatigue limits Cycle time studies, design and process validation, user comfort, reachability, and line of sight are other human-factors that may be examined in ergonomic simulation packages.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Modeling and simulation of a task can be performed by manually manipulating the virtual human in the simulated environment.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Some ergonomics simulation software permits interactive, real-time simulation and evaluation through actual human input via motion capture technologies.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] However, motion capture for ergonomics requires expensive equipment and the creation of props to represent the environment or product.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Some applications of ergonomic simulation in include analysis of solid waste collection, disaster management tasks, interactive gaming, automotive assembly line, virtual prototyping of rehabilitation aids, and aerospace product design.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Ford engineers use ergonomics simulation software to perform virtual product design reviews.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Using engineering data, the simulations assist evaluation of assembly ergonomics.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] The company uses Siemen's Jack and Jill ergonomics simulation software in improving worker safety and efficiency, without the need to build expensive prototypes.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] In finance, computer simulations are often used for scenario planning.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Risk-adjusted net present value, for example, is computed from well-defined but not always known (or fixed) inputs.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] By imitating the performance of the project under evaluation, simulation can provide a distribution of NPV over a range of discount rates and other variables.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Simulations are also often used to test a financial theory or the ability of a financial model.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Simulations are frequently used in financial training to engage participants in experiencing various historical as well as fictional situations.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] There are stock market simulations, portfolio simulations, risk management simulations or models and forex simulations.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Such simulations are typically based on stochastic asset models.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Using these simulations in a training program allows for the application of theory into a something akin to real life.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] As with other industries, the use of simulations can be technology or case-study driven.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Flight simulation is mainly used to train pilots outside of the aircraft.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] In comparison to training in flight, simulation-based training allows for practicing maneuvers or situations that may be impractical (or even dangerous) to perform in the aircraft while keeping the pilot and instructor in a relatively low-risk environment on the ground.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] For example, electrical system failures, instrument failures, hydraulic system failures, and even flight control failures can be simulated without risk to the crew or equipment.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Instructors can also provide students with a higher concentration of training tasks in a given period of time than is usually possible in the aircraft.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Flight simulation also provides an economic advantage over training in an actual aircraft.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Once fuel, maintenance, and insurance costs are taken into account, the operating costs of an FSTD are usually substantially lower than the operating costs of the simulated aircraft.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] For some large transport category airplanes, the operating costs may be several times lower for the FSTD than the actual aircraft.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Another advantage is reduced environmental impact, as simulators don't contribute directly to carbon or noise emissions.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] There also exist "engineering flight simulators" which are a key element of the aircraft design process.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Many benefits that come from a lower number of test flights like cost and safety improvements are described above, but there are some unique advantages.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Having a simulator available allows for faster design iteration cycle or using more test equipment than could be fit into a real aircraft.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Bearing resemblance to flight simulators, a **marine simulator** is meant for training of ship personnel.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Simulators like these are mostly used within maritime colleges, training institutions, and navies.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] They often consist of a replication of a ships' bridge, with the operating console(s), and a number of screens on which the virtual surroundings are projected.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Military simulations, also known informally as war games, are models in which theories of warfare can be tested and refined without the need for actual hostilities.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] They exist in many different forms, with varying degrees of realism.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] In recent times, their scope has widened to include not only military but also political and social factors (for example, the Nationlab series of strategic exercises in Latin America).
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] While many governments make use of simulation, both individually and collaboratively, little is known about the model's specifics outside professional circles.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Network and distributed systems have been extensively simulated in other to understand the impact of new protocols and algorithms before their deployment in the actual systems.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] The simulation can focus on different levels (physical layer, network layer, application layer), and evaluate different metrics (network bandwidth, resource consumption, service time, dropped packets, system availability).
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Simulation techniques have also been applied to payment and securities settlement systems.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Among the main users are central banks, which are generally responsible for the oversight of market infrastructure and are entitled to contribute to the smooth functioning of payment systems.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Central banks have been using payment system simulations to evaluate things such as the adequacy or sufficiency of liquidity available ( in the form of account balances and intraday credit limits) to participants (mainly banks) to allow efficient settlement of payments.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] The need for liquidity is also dependent on the availability and the type of netting procedures in the systems, thus some of the studies have a focus on system comparisons.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Another application is to evaluate risks related to events such as communication network breakdowns or the inability of participants to send payments (e.g. in case of possible bank failure).
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] This kind of analysis falls under the concepts of stress testing or scenario analysis.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] A common way to conduct these simulations is to replicate the settlement logics of the real payment or securities settlement systems under analysis and then use real observed payment data.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] In case of system comparison or system development, naturally, also the other settlement logics need to be implemented.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] To perform stress testing and scenario analysis, the observed data needs to be altered, e.g. some payments delayed or removed.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] To analyze the levels of liquidity, initial liquidity levels are varied.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] System comparisons (benchmarking) or evaluations of new netting algorithms or rules are performed by running simulations with a fixed set of data and varying only the system setups.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] An inference is usually done by comparing the benchmark simulation results to the results of altered simulation setups by comparing indicators such as unsettled transactions or settlement delays.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Project management simulation is simulation used for project management training and analysis.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] It is often used as a training simulation for project managers.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] In other cases, it is used for what-if analysis and for supporting decision-making in real projects.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Frequently the simulation is conducted using software tools.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] A robotics simulator is used to create embedded applications for a specific (or not) robot without being dependent on the 'real' robot.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] In some cases, these applications can be transferred to the real robot (or rebuilt) without modifications.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Robotics simulators allow reproducing situations that cannot be 'created' in the real world because of cost, time, or the 'uniqueness' of a resource.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] A simulator also allows fast robot prototyping.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Many robot simulators feature physics engines to simulate a robot's dynamics.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Such simulations can help predict the impact of how improvements in methods might impact variability, cost, labor time, and the number of transactions at various stages in the process.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] A full-featured computerized process simulator can be used to depict such models, as can simpler educational demonstrations using spreadsheet software, pennies being transferred between cups based on the roll of a die, or dipping into a tub of colored beads with a scoop.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] In sports, computer simulations are often done to predict the outcome of events and the performance of individual sportspeople.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] They attempt to recreate the event through models built from statistics.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] The increase in technology has allowed anyone with knowledge of programming the ability to run simulations of their models.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] The simulations are built from a series of mathematical algorithms, or models, and can vary with accuracy.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Accuscore, which is licensed by companies such as ESPN, is a well-known simulation program for all major sports.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] It offers a detailed analysis of games through simulated betting lines, projected point totals and overall probabilities.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] With the increased interest in fantasy sports simulation models that predict individual player performance have gained popularity.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Companies like What If Sports and StatFox specialize in not only using their simulations for predicting game results but how well individual players will do as well.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Many people use models to determine whom to start in their fantasy leagues.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Another way simulations are helping the sports field is in the use of biomechanics.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Models are derived and simulations are run from data received from sensors attached to athletes and video equipment.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Sports biomechanics aided by simulation models answer questions regarding training techniques such as the effect of fatigue on throwing performance (height of throw) and biomechanical factors of the upper limbs (reactive strength index; hand contact time).
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Computer simulations allow their users to take models which before were too complex to run, and give them answers.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Simulations have proven to be some of the best insights into both play performance and team predictability.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Simulation was used at Kennedy Space Center (KSC) to train and certify Space Shuttle engineers during simulated launch countdown operations.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] The Space Shuttle engineering community would participate in a launch countdown integrated simulation before each Shuttle flight.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] This simulation is a virtual simulation where real people interact with simulated Space Shuttle vehicle and Ground Support Equipment (GSE) hardware.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] The Shuttle Final Countdown Phase Simulation, also known as S0044, involved countdown processes that would integrate many of the Space Shuttle vehicle and GSE systems.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Some of the Shuttle systems integrated in the simulation are the main propulsion system, RS-25, solid rocket boosters, ground liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen, external tank, flight controls, navigation, and avionics.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] The Shuttle Final Countdown Phase Simulation took place at the Kennedy Space Center Launch Control Center firing rooms.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] The firing room used during the simulation is the same control room where real launch countdown operations are executed.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] As a result, equipment used for real launch countdown operations is engaged.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] The Space Shuttle vehicle hardware and related GSE hardware is simulated by mathematical models (written in Shuttle Ground Operations Simulator (SGOS) modeling language) that behave and react like real hardware.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] During the Shuttle Final Countdown Phase Simulation, engineers command and control hardware via real application software executing in the control consoles – just as if they were commanding real vehicle hardware.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] However, these real software applications do not interface with real Shuttle hardware during simulations.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Instead, the applications interface with mathematical model representations of the vehicle and GSE hardware.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Consequently, the simulations bypass sensitive and even dangerous mechanisms while providing engineering measurements detailing how the hardware would have reacted.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Since these math models interact with the command and control application software, models and simulations are also used to debug and verify the functionality of application software.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] The only true way to test GNSS receivers (commonly known as Sat-Nav's in the commercial world) is by using an RF Constellation Simulator.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] A receiver that may, for example, be used on an aircraft, can be tested under dynamic conditions without the need to take it on a real flight.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] The test conditions can be repeated exactly, and there is full control over all the test parameters. this is not possible in the 'real-world' using the actual signals.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] For testing receivers that will use the new Galileo (satellite navigation) there is no alternative, as the real signals do not yet exist.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Predicting weather conditions by extrapolating/interpolating previous data is one of the real use of simulation.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Most of the weather forecasts use this information published by Weather bureaus.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] This kind of simulations helps in predicting and forewarning about extreme weather conditions like the path of an active hurricane/cyclone.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Numerical weather prediction for forecasting involves complicated numeric computer models to predict weather accurately by taking many parameters into account.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Strategy games—both traditional and modern—may be viewed as simulations of abstracted decision-making for the purpose of training military and political leaders (see History of Go for an example of such a tradition, or Kriegsspiel for a more recent example).
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Many other video games are simulators of some kind.
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] Such games can simulate various aspects of reality, from business, to government, to construction, to piloting vehicles (see above).
[src:digital-twin/simulation-p02] However, the connection between simulation and dissembling later faded out and is now only of linguistic interest.
